'''Walter Anthony "Tony" Comerford''' (January 25, 1898 &ndash; August 25, 1970) was an American [[college football]] and [[college basketball|basketball]] coach, university [[athletic director]], [[minor league baseball]] player, government official, and [[United States Marine Corps|United States Marine]]. He served as the head football and basketball coach at the [[Loyola University Maryland|Loyola College of Maryland]] from 1928 to 1933.

==Early life==
A native of [[Worcester, Massachusetts]],<ref name=pupils>[http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/1650810852.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Dec+31%2C+1926&author=&pub=Boston+Daily+Globe+%281923-1927%29&desc=TWO+EX-B.+C.+PUPILS+TO+AID+CAVANAUGH&pqatl=google TWO EX-B. C. PUPILS TO AID CAVANAUGH; Comerford and McNamara Get Fordham Posts Joy Also to Be an Assistant, but Doyle Declines.], ''Boston Daily Globe'', December 31, 1926.</ref> Comerford served in the [[United States Marine Corps]] during [[World War I]].<ref name=bc>[http://bceagles.cstv.com/genrel/comerford_tony00.html Tony Comerford], Boston College, retrieved August 16, 2011.</ref> He attended [[Boston College]], where he played on the [[Boston College football|football team]] as an [[end (American football)|end]] from 1919 to 1922, and was the team captain in 1921.<ref>[http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/bc/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/07guide-5.pdf ''2007 Boston College Football Media Guide''] (PDF), p. 157, Boston College, 2007.</ref><ref name=obit>[http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/1946637922.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+26%2C+1970&author=&pub=Boston+Globe+%281960-1979%29&desc=Tony+Comerford+dies%3B+BC+football+end%2C+1918-22&pqatl=google Tony Comerford dies; BC football end, 1918-22], ''Boston Globe'', August 26, 1970.</ref> Comerford also played [[Boston College Eagles baseball|baseball]] and ran [[track & field|track]] for Boston College.<ref>[http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/864824752.html?dids=864824752:864824752&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&date=Apr+28%2C+1923&author=&pub=Boston+Daily+Globe&desc=B.+C.+SLUGGERS+HIT+THREE+CIRCUIT+SWATS&pqatl=google B.C. Sluggers Hit Three Circuit Swats], ''Boston Daily Globe'', April 28, 1923.</ref><ref>[http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VwsrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D5oFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5111,3259404&dq=comerford&hl=en Comerford Dies, Ex-College Gridder], ''Reading Eagle'', August 26, 1970.</ref>

==Coaching career==
After graduating in 1923,<ref name=bc/> Comerford played minor league baseball for the Star Taxis club in [[Lewiston, Maine]].<ref>[http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xnQpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hWYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1300,362430&dq=tony-comerford&hl=en Former Boston College Stars Now With Taxis], ''Lewiston Evening Journal'', July 6, 1923.</ref> In the fall, he coached the football team at [[Dummer Academy]] in [[Byfield, Massachusetts|South Byfield, Massachusetts]].<ref>[http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_3QpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hWYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1273,5423290&dq=comerford+dummer+academy&hl=en Comerford to Coach at Dummer Academy], ''Lewiston Evening Journal'', September 13, 1923.</ref> The following season, he played minor league baseball with the [[Everett, Massachusetts|Everett]] club of the Boston Twilight League.<ref>[http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=w7kgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=emkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1464,6067111&dq=tony-comerford&hl=en Opening of Interstate League at Dixfield and Berlin, N.H., Parks Today], ''The Lewiston Daily Sun'', June 25, 1924.</ref>

In 1924, Comerford coached the [[Naval Station Newport|Newport Naval Training Station]] football team.<ref>[http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_vViAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HmQNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1515,1873699&dq=tony-comerford&hl=en Just an Earful], ''Evening Tribune'', September 17, 1924.</ref> He returned to his alma mater to coach the Boston College [[End (American football)|ends]] under [[Frank Cavanaugh (American football)|Frank Cavanaugh]] during the 1926 season.<ref>[http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/1650993642.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Sep+07%2C+1926&author=&pub=Boston+Daily+Globe+%281923-1927%29&desc=B.+C.+FOOTBALL+MEN+WILL+REPORT+TODAY&pqatl=google B. C. FOOTBALL MEN WILL REPORT TODAY; Candidates to Have Light Drill After Lunch Wealth of Backfield Material but Some Gaps In Line], ''Boston Daily Globe'', Sep 7, 1926.</ref> In 1927, he followed Cavanaugh to [[Fordham University]] to serve as an assistant coach and the freshman coach.<Ref name=pupils/>

In March 1928, [[Loyola University Maryland|Loyola College]] in [[Baltimore]] hired Comerford as its [[athletic director]] and coach.<ref>[http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/1998559392.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Mar+04%2C+1928&author=&pub=Daily+Boston+Globe+%281928-1960%29&desc=COMERFORD+NAMED+COACH+AT+LOYOLA&pqatl=google COMERFORD NAMED COACH AT LOYOLA; Ex-B. C. Three-Sport Star to Fill Baltimore Post Worcester Man Member of Famous 1920 Eagle Eleven], ''Daily Boston Globe'', Mar 4, 1928.</ref> He served as the school's football coach from 1928 to 1933 and basketball coach for the 1928&ndash;29 season and from 1930 to 1934. His basketball teams amassed a 43&ndash;34 record.<ref>[http://www.loyolagreyhounds.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/locl/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/MBBRecordBook 2010&ndash;2011 Loyola University Maryland Men's Basketball], p. 16, Loyola University Maryland, 2010.</ref> During the 1932 season, the football team traveled to his alma mater, Boston College, to play the dedication game at newly renovated Alumni Field. Boston College won, 14&ndash;0.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=jfwyQ4CG1fcC ''Tales from the Boston College Sideline''], p. 105, Sports Publishing LLC, 2004, ISBN 1582615462.</ref> Loyola discontinued its football program after the 1933 season, and Comerford left the school.<ref>[http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/baltsun/access/1672175432.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+07%2C+1935&author=&pub=The+Sun+%281837-1985%29&desc=VARSITY+VIEWS&pqatl=google VARSITY VIEWS], ''The Baltimore Sun'', January 7, 1935.</ref> In 1934, while an assistant at [[Canisius College]], he filled in for head coach William Joy, who had been seriously injured in an automobile accident.<ref>[http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB081FFF395B107A93C7AB1782D85F408385F9 CANISIUS COACH INJURED; Joy Seriously Hurt in Automobile Accident Near Hamilton], ''The New York Times'', September 25, 1934.</ref> [[Saint Anselm College]] hired Comerford as its head football coach in 1941.<ref>[http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0710FD3859167B93CAAB1789D85F458485F9 St. Anselm's Names Comerford], ''The New York Times'', Feb 28, 1941.</ref> He remained there for one season and finished with a 1&ndash;6 record.<ref>[http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=4777 Walter Commerford Records by Year], College Football Data Warehouse, retrieved August 16, 2011.</ref>

==Later life==
By 1943, he was seated on the Massachusetts State Parole Board.<ref>[http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/2049667682.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Oct+20%2C+1943&author=&pub=Daily+Boston+Globe+%281928-1960%29&desc=%27Cav%27+Film+Brings+B.+C.+1919+Team+Together+Again&pqatl=google 'Cav' Film Brings B. C. 1919 Team Together Again], ''Daily Boston Globe'', Oct 20, 1943.</ref> In 1951, he was appointed as the executive assistant to Boston Mayor [[John Hynes]] for Region Five of the Civil Defense Agency.<ref>[http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/2064302582.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+20%2C+1951&author=&pub=Daily+Boston+Globe+%281928-1960%29&desc=Comerford+to+Be+Aid+to+Hynes+in+Civil+Defense&pqatl=google Comerford to Be Aid to Hynes in Civil Defense], ''Daily Boston Globe'', Jan 20, 1951.</ref> Comerford died at St. Elizabeth's Hospital in [[Brighton, Massachusetts]] on August 25, 1970 at the age of 72.<ref name=obit/> The Boston College Varsity Club Athletic Hall of Fame inducted him in 1982.<ref name=bc/>

